"Den Elzen M., Schaeffer M.","Responsibility for past and future global warming: Uncertainties in attributing anthropogenic climate change",2002,"Climatic Change","54","1-2",,"29","73",,,10.1023/A:1015750019028,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0036289738&partnerID=40&md5=8d6f2fe1000f880a0f71d3d49a16a681","Dutch National Institute for Public Health and the Environment (RIVM), P.O. Box 1, Bilthoven 3720 BA, Netherlands; Royal Dutch Meteorological Institute (KNMI), P.O. Box 201, De Bilt 3730 AE, Netherlands","Den Elzen, M., Dutch National Institute for Public Health and the Environment (RIVM), P.O. Box 1, Bilthoven 3720 BA, Netherlands; Schaeffer, M., Dutch National Institute for Public Health and the Environment (RIVM), P.O. Box 1, Bilthoven 3720 BA, Netherlands, Royal Dutch Meteorological Institute (KNMI), P.O. Box 201, De Bilt 3730 AE, Netherlands","During the negotiations on the Kyoto Protocol, Brazil proposed a methodology to link the relative contribution of Annex I Parties to emission reductions with the relative contributions of Parties to the global-mean temperature increase. The proposal was not adopted during the negotiations but referred to the Subsidiary Body for Scientific and Technological Advice for consideration of its methodological aspects. In this context we analyze the impact of model uncertainties and methodological choices on the regionally attributed global-mean temperature increase. A climate assessment model has been developed to calculate changes in greenhouse gas concentrations, global-mean temperature and sea-level rise attributable to individual regions. The analysis shows the impact of the different choices in methodological aspects to be as important as the impact of model uncertainties on a region's contribution to present and future global temperature increases. Choices may be the inclusion of the anthropogenic non-CO2 greenhouse gas emissions and/or the CO2 emissions associated with land-use changes. When responsibility to global temperature change is attributed to all emitting Parties, the impacts of modeling uncertainties and methodological choices on contributions of individual Parties are considerable. However, if relative contributions are calculated only within the group of Annex I countries, the results are less sensitive to the uncertainty aspects considered here.",,"Carbon dioxide; Greenhouse effect; Thermal effects; Emission reductions; Global warming; anthropogenic effect; climate change; global warming",,,,,,"Alcamo, J., IMAGE 2.0: Integrated modeling of global climate change (1994) Water Air Soil Pollut., 76, pp. 1-2; Alcamo, J., Kreileman, G.J.J., Bollen, J.C., Van den Born, G.J., Gerlagh, R., Krol, M.S., Toet, A.M.C., De Vries, H.J.M., Baseline scenarios of global environmental change (1996) Global Environ. Change, 6, pp. 261-303; Alcamo, J., Leemans, R., Kreileman, G.J.J., (1998) Global Change Scenarios of the 21st Century. Results from the IMAGE 2.1 Model, , Elsevier Science, London; Andres, R.J., Fielding, D.J., Marland, G., Boden, T.A., Kumar, N., Carbon dioxide emissions from fossil fuel use, 1751-1950 (1999) Tellus, 51 B, pp. 759-765. , This data set has been integrated into CDIAC data set NDP-030 'Global, Regional, and National CO2 Emission Estimates from Fossil Fuel Burning, Cement Production, and Gas Flaring, 1751-1996'; Andronova, N., Schlesinger, M.E., Causes of global temperature changes during the 19th and 20th centuries (2000) Geophys. Res. Lett., 27, pp. 2137-2140; Berk, M.M., Den Elzen, M.G.J., The Brazilian proposal evaluated (1998) CHANGE, 44, pp. 19-23; Cess, R.D., Potter, G.L., Blancher, J.P., Boer, G.J., Ghan, S.J., Kiehl, J.T., Le Treut, H., Yagai, I., Interpretation of cloud-climate feedback as produced by 14 atmospheric general circulation models (1989) Science, 245, pp. 513-516; Cramer, W., Bondeau, A., Woodward, F.I., Prentice, I.C., Betts, R.A., Brovkin, V., Cox, P.M., Young-Molling, C., Global reponse of terrestrial ecosystem structur